{"type":"message","id":"389c5f3e","parentId":"d60b9d97","timestamp":"2026-05-28T17:43:57.610Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Oh no - the symlink doesn't exist anymore (got deleted by my `rm` command), and the original file is also gone (because `rm` through the symlink deleted the original). So the album images directory is now empty and the only photo record in the database still references ALB-20260528-0002.jpg which no longer exists!\n\nLet me check if the database still has the record. I need to recreate the file. Let me check if there's a backup somewhere.\n\nActually, wait - let me re-read my earlier commands. I ran:\n1. `ln -sf /root/.openclaw/workspace-son/album/images /root/.openclaw/workspace-father/son-album-images` - created symlink\n2. Then the cp command that said \"are the same file\" - because symlink pointed to the same location\n3. Then `rm /root/.openclaw/workspace-father/son-album-images/ALB-20260528-0002.jpg` - this deleted the original file through the symlink!\n4. Then `rm /root/.openclaw/workspace-father/son-album-images` - this deleted the symlink itself\n\nSo the only real JPEG in the album is gone now. Let me check if there's something I can do to recover it, or if the file is truly lost.\n\nWait, actually looking at the image command output more carefully. Earlier when I ran the `image` tool with the symlink path, it said:\n```\nLocal media path is not under an allowed directory: /root/.openclaw/workspace-father/son-album-images/ALB-20260528-0002.jpg\n```\n\nBut this is AFTER the file was deleted by the rm command. So the image tool failed because the file doesn't exist AND it's not under the allowed directory.\n\nLet me check if the original file still exists somewhere. The `rm` through the symlink would have deleted it from the original location.\n\nThe file is gone. I messed up. Let me check if it's still referenced in the database and see if maybe the media directory has a backup.\n\nActually,